---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const title = 'Terms of Use — Plnt';
const description = 'Terms of use for the Plnt project and website.';
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} path="/terms">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose" style="max-width: 760px;">
      <span class="eyebrow">legal</span>
      <h1>Terms of Use</h1>
      <p class="muted">Last updated: June 15, 2026</p>

      <h2>1. The software</h2>
      <p>
        Plnt is open-source software released under the <strong>Apache License 2.0</strong>.
        Your use of the software is governed by that license. Nothing on this website
        modifies, supersedes, or grants any rights beyond the license text itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        The full license is available in the <a href="https://github.com/plnt-work/plnt/blob/main/LICENSE" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LICENSE file</a> of the repository.
      </p>

      <h2>2. This website</h2>
      <p>
        This site (<code>plnt.dev</code>) is informational. It describes the Plnt project and
        links to source code, documentation, and resources. No accounts, no purchases,
        no user-submitted content.
      </p>

      <h2>3. No warranty</h2>
      <p>
        The software is provided <strong>"as is"</strong>, without warranty of any kind, express
        or implied. Plnt runs agents on your machine that read your files and may execute
        commands you authorize. You are responsible for understanding what you run.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Plnt does not ship telemetry. No data leaves your machine unless you point it at a cloud LLM backend.</li>
        <li>The sandbox is a ladder — the default <code>process</code> rung is not a security boundary against malicious code you choose to execute.</li>
        <li>Sub-agents may issue shell commands. Review the JSONL audit log in <code>$PLNT_HOME/runs/</code> if in doubt.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>4. Third-party services</h2>
      <p>
        Plnt can route inference to third-party providers (OpenAI, Groq, Together, OpenRouter,
        Anthropic, etc.) if you configure them. Your use of those providers is governed by
        <em>their</em> terms and privacy policies, not ours. Plnt itself does not relay
        anything through our infrastructure.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Contributions</h2>
      <p>
        Contributions to the repository are accepted under the Apache-2.0 license. By
        submitting a pull request you certify the contribution is yours to license under
        Apache-2.0 (a Developer Certificate of Origin equivalent).
      </p>

      <h2>6. Trademark</h2>
      <p>
        "Plnt" and the wordmark may be used to refer to the project. You may not use them
        to imply endorsement of a different product or to brand a fork in a way that
        confuses users.
      </p>

      <h2>7. Changes</h2>
      <p>
        These terms may be updated. The latest version is always at <a href="/terms">plnt.dev/terms</a>. Material changes will be noted at the top of this page.
      </p>

      <hr/>
      <p class="dim">
        Questions? Open an issue on <a href="https://github.com/plnt-work/plnt/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
